SIMPLE: astound
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Astound
<hw>As*tound"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>astouned</ets>, <ets>astound</ets>, <ets>astoned</ets>, p. p. of
<ets>astone</ets>. See <er>Astone</er>.]</ety> <def>Stunned; astounded;
astonished.</def> <mark>[Archaic]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thus Ellen, dizzy and <qex>astound</qex>.⟦br⟧
As sudden ruin yawned around.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Astound</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Astound
<hw>As*tound"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Astounded</conjf>, <mark>[Obs.]</mark> <conjf>Astound</conjf>;
<pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Astounding</conjf>.]</vmorph>
<ety>[See <er>Astound</er>, <pos>a.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
stun; to stupefy.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No puissant stroke his senses once <qex>astound</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Fairfax.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To astonish; to strike with amazement; to confound
with wonder, surprise, or fear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>These thoughts may startle well, but not <qex>astound</qex>⟦br⟧
The virtuous mind.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>astounded</ent>⟦br⟧
